<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-533-999  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 533 999.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Oct 22 1990 v4 n37 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI system would exchange mug shots, prints with squad cars.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FBI plans an image transmission system wherein fingerprintsand mug shots of fugitives can be sent directly to or from policesquad cars across the country.andP;  The FBI has completed theyear-long pilot of the system with Fingermatrix Inc a biometricsecurity systems company.andP;  The pilot system featured a standardtwo-way police radio for analog image transmission.andP;  With thissystem, the police will not have to buy new communicationsequipment if the pilot goes into effect.andP;  The FBI hopes that thesystem becomes part of its National Crime Information Center NCIC2000 an ambitious project designed to overhaul the outdated NCIC.andO;FBI sources note that although the system is a priority the agencywill have to overcome the usual budgetary constraints.andP;  Theprevious request for $17 million was rejected by the Office ofManagement and Budget.andP;  But the Senate may restore this amountduring negotiations.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Fingermatrix Inc. (Products).andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationImaging TechnologyGovernment FundingInvestigationsRadio CommunicationRadio EquipmentPilot ProjectsSecurity Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>